		},
  title	      =	{Detecting Botnets with Tight Command and Control},
  booktitle   =	{Proceedings of the 31st IEEE Conference on Local Computer
		Networks},
  year	      =	{2006},
  pages	      =	{195--202},
  keywords    =	{botnets},
  url	      =	{http://www.ir.bbn.com/documents/articles/botnet-lcn-06.pdf},
  abstract    =	{Systems are attempting to detect botnets by examining
		traffic content for IRC commands or by setting up honeynets.
		Our approach for detecting botnets is to examine flow
		characteristics such as bandwidth, duration, and packet
		timing looking for evidence of botnet command and control
		activity. We have constructed an architecture that first
		eliminates traffic that is unlikely to be a part of a botnet,
		classifies the remaining traffic into a group that is likely
		to be part of a botnet, then correlates the likely traffic to
		find common communications patterns that would suggest the
		activity of a botnet. Our results show that botnet evidence
		can be extracted from a traffic trace containing almost 9
		million flows.},
